[{"category":"section","location":"#Optikos.jl","page":"Home","text":"A general purpose optics package for Julia.","title":"Optikos.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"#Types","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Types"},{"category":"section","location":"#Grids","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Grids"},{"category":"section","location":"#Fields","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Fields"},{"category":"section","location":"#Beams","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Beams"},{"category":"section","location":"#Functions","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Functions"},{"category":"section","location":"#Manual-Outline","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Manual Outline"},{"category":"section","location":"#Examples","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Examples"},{"category":"section","location":"#Gaussian-Beams","page":"Home","text":"using Optikos\nusing CairoMakie\n\ngrid = TransverseGrid(range(-1e-3, 1e-3, 256), range(-1e-3, 1e-3, 256))\nbeam = GaussianBeam(200e-6, 632.8e-9)\nfield = evaluate(grid, beam)\n\nfig, ax, hm = heatmap(grid.x * 1e3, grid.y * 1e3, intensity(field))\nax.xlabel = \"x [mm]\"\nax.ylabel = \"y [mm]\"\nax.title  = \"Gaussian beam intensity\"\nColorbar(fig[1,2], hm)\nfig","title":"Gaussian Beams"},{"category":"section","location":"#Laguerre-Gaussian-Beams","page":"Home","text":"using Optikos\nusing CairoMakie\n\ngrid = TransverseGrid(range(-1e-3, 1e-3, 256), range(-1e-3, 1e-3, 256))\nbeam = LGBeam(200e-6, 632.8e-9, 0, 1)\nfield = evaluate(grid, beam)\n\nfig, ax, hm = heatmap(grid.x * 1e3, grid.y * 1e3, intensity(field))\nax.xlabel = \"x [mm]\"\nax.ylabel = \"y [mm]\"\nax.title  = \"LG beam (p=0, l=1) intensity\"\nColorbar(fig[1,2], hm)\nfig","title":"Laguerre-Gaussian Beams"},{"category":"section","location":"#Visualization","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Visualization"},{"category":"section","location":"#Index","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Index"},{"category":"type","location":"#Optikos.TransverseGrid","page":"Home","text":"TransverseGrid(x::Vector{Float64}[, y::Vector{Float64}])\n\nA uniform transverse sampling grid for field representation.\n\nArguments\n\nx: x-axis sample points [m]\ny: y-axis sample points [m]\n\nFields\n\nx, y: coordinate vectors [m] (Vector{Float64})\nNx, Ny: number of sample points (Int)\ndx, dy: sample spacing [m] (Float64)\n\nExamples\n\njulia> x = range(-1e-3, 1e-3, length=256);\n\njulia> y = range(-1e-3, 1e-3, length=256);\n\njulia> grid = TransverseGrid(x, y);\n\njulia> grid = TransverseGrid(x);\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Optikos.TransverseGrid"},{"category":"type","location":"#Optikos.ScalarField","page":"Home","text":"ScalarField(U::Matrix{ComplexF64}, grid::TransverseGrid, λ::Float64)\n\nA transverse scalar field representation type.\n\nArguments\n\nU: Complex amplitude [V/m]\ngrid: A uniform transverse grid associated with the complex amplitude\nλ: Wavelength [m]\n\nExamples\n\njulia> x = y = range(-1e-3, 1e-3, length=256);\n\njulia> grid = TransverseGrid(x, y);\n\njulia> λ = 600e-9;\n\njulia> U = ones(ComplexF64, (256, 256));\n\njulia> field = ScalarField(U, grid, λ);\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Optikos.ScalarField"},{"category":"type","location":"#Optikos.SphericalBeam","page":"Home","text":"SphericalBeam(λ::Float64, z; n_index=1.0)\n\nAnalytical descriptor of a spherical beam.\n\nFields\n\nλ: wavelength [m]\nz: axial position of the transverse beam profile assuming origin at z=0 [m]\nn_index: refractive index of the propagation medium\n\nExamples\n\njulia> beam = SphericalBeam(632.8e-9, 0.1);\n\nReferences\n\nSaleh & Teich, Fundamentals of Photonics, 3rd ed., §2.2\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Optikos.SphericalBeam"},{"category":"type","location":"#Optikos.GaussianBeam","page":"Home","text":"GaussianBeam(w0::Float64, λ::Float64; z0=0.0, n_index=1.0)\n\nAnalytical descriptor of a fundamental Gaussian beam (TEM₀₀).\n\nFields\n\nw0: beam waist radius [m]\nλ: wavelength [m]\nz0: axial position of the transverse beam profile assuming origin at z=0 [m]\nn_index: refractive index of the propagation medium\n\nExamples\n\njulia> beam = GaussianBeam(200e-6, 632.8e-9);\n\njulia> beam.w0\n0.0002\n\njulia> beam.n_index\n1.0\n\nReferences\n\nSaleh & Teich, Fundamentals of Photonics, 3rd ed., §3.1\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Optikos.GaussianBeam"},{"category":"type","location":"#Optikos.LGBeam","page":"Home","text":"LGBeam(w0::Float64, λ::Float64, p::Int, l::Int; z0=0.0, n_index=1.0)\n\nAnalytical descriptor of a Laguerre-Gaussian beam LG(p, l).\n\nCarries orbital angular momentum of l·ħ per photon. The azimuthal index l determines the topological charge of the optical vortex, and p is the number of radial nodes.\n\nFields\n\nw0: beam waist radius [m]\nλ: wavelength [m]\np: radial index (p ≥ 0)\nl: azimuthal index / topological charge (integer)\nz0: axial position of the transverse beam profile assuming origin at z=0 [m]\nn_index: refractive index of the propagation medium\n\nExamples\n\njulia> beam = LGBeam(100e-6, 532e-9, 0, 1);\n\njulia> beam.l   # topological charge\n1\n\njulia> beam.p   # radial index\n0\n\nReferences\n\nAllen et al., Phys. Rev. A 45, 8185 (1992) Saleh & Teich, Fundamentals of Photonics, 3rd ed., §3.3\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Optikos.LGBeam"},{"category":"type","location":"#Optikos.HGBeam","page":"Home","text":"HGBeam(w0::Float64, λ::Float64, m::Int, n::Int; z0=0.0, n_index=1.0)\n\nAnalytical descriptor of a Hermite-Gaussian beam HG(m, n).\n\nRectangular-symmetry transverse modes. The indices m and n_order give the number of nodes along the x and y axes respectively.\n\nFields\n\nw0   : beam waist radius [m]\nλ    : wavelength [m]\nm    : mode index along x (m ≥ 0)\nn    : mode index along y (n ≥ 0)\nz0: axial position of the transverse beam profile assuming origin at z=0 [m]\nn_index : refractive index of the propagation medium\n\nExamples\n\njulia> beam = HGBeam(150e-6, 1064e-9, 1, 0);\n\njulia> beam.m\n1\n\njulia> beam.n\n0\n\nReferences\n\nSaleh & Teich, Fundamentals of Photonics, 3rd ed., §3.3\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Optikos.HGBeam"},{"category":"function","location":"#Optikos.evaluate","page":"Home","text":"evaluate(grid::TransverseGrid{<:Real}, beam::SphericalBeam) -> ScalarField\n\nSample a Spherical beam onto a transverse grid at the plane z = z0.\n\nThe complex field amplitude at the waist (z = 0) is:\n\nU(r) = fracA_0rexpleft(-jkrright)\n\nArguments\n\ngrid: TransverseGrid on which to sample\nbeam: GaussianBeam descriptor\n\nReturns\n\nA ScalarField with unit peak amplitude at the waist.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> grid  = TransverseGrid(range(-1e-3, 1e-3, 64), range(-1e-3, 1e-3, 64));\n\njulia> beam  = SphericalBeam(632.8e-9, 0.1);\n\njulia> field = evaluate(grid, beam);\n\njulia> size(field.U)\n(64, 64)\n\nReferences\n\nSaleh & Teich, Fundamentals of Photonics, 3rd ed., §2.2\n\n\n\n\n\nevaluate(grid::TransverseGrid{<:Real}, beam::GaussianBeam) -> ScalarField\n\nSample a Gaussian beam onto a transverse grid at the plane z = z0.\n\nThe complex field amplitude at the waist (z = 0) is:\n\nU(x y) = expleft(-fracx^2 + y^2w_0^2right)\n\nFor z ≠ 0, the full Gaussian beam expression including the beam radius w(z), wavefront curvature R(z), and Gouy phase ψ(z) is used:\n\nU(x y z) = fracw_0w(z)\nexpleft(-fracr^2w(z)^2right)\nexpleft(-ileft(kz + frackr^22R(z) - psi(z)right)right)\n\nwhere:\n\nw(z) = w_0sqrt1 + (zz_R)^2\nR(z) = zleft(1 + (z_Rz)^2right)\npsi(z) = arctan(zz_R)\nz_R = pi w_0^2 n  lambda is the Rayleigh range\n\nArguments\n\nbeam: GaussianBeam descriptor\ngrid: TransverseGrid on which to sample\n\nReturns\n\nA ScalarField with unit peak amplitude at the waist.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> grid  = TransverseGrid(range(-1e-3, 1e-3, 64), range(-1e-3, 1e-3, 64));\n\njulia> beam  = GaussianBeam(200e-6, 632.8e-9);\n\njulia> field = evaluate(grid, beam);\n\njulia> size(field.U)\n(64, 64)\n\nReferences\n\nSaleh & Teich, Fundamentals of Photonics, 3rd ed., §3.1\n\n\n\n\n\nevaluate(grid::TransverseGrid{<:Real}, beam::LGBeam) -> ScalarField\n\nSample a Laguerre-Gaussian beam LG(p, l) onto a transverse grid at z = z0.\n\nThe complex field amplitude at the waist is:\n\nU(r phi) = left(fracrsqrt2w_0right)^l\nL_p^lleft(frac2r^2w_0^2right)\nexpleft(-fracr^2w_0^2right)\nexp(-ilphi)\n\nwhere L_p^l is the generalized Laguerre polynomial.\n\nArguments\n\ngrid: TransverseGrid on which to evaluate\nbeam: LGBeam descriptor\n\nReturns\n\nA ScalarField with the LG modal amplitude.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> grid = TransverseGrid(range(-1e-3, 1e-3, 64), range(-1e-3, 1e-3, 64));\n\njulia> beam = LGBeam(200e-6, 632.8e-9, 0, 3);\n\njulia> field = evaluate(grid, beam);\n\njulia> abs2(field.U[32, 32]) < 1e3   # vortex: zero on axis for l≠0\ntrue\n\nReferences\n\nAllen et al., Phys. Rev. A 45, 8185 (1992) Saleh & Teich, Fundamentals of Photonics, 3rd ed., §3.3\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Optikos.evaluate"},{"category":"function","location":"#Optikos.fieldplot","page":"Home","text":"No docstring defined.\n\nPlot type\n\nThe plot type alias for the fieldplot function is FieldPlot.\n\nAttributes\n\nunits =  :mm  — Defines the units of the plot\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Optikos.fieldplot"},{"category":"function","location":"#Optikos.fieldplot!","page":"Home","text":"fieldplot! is the mutating variant of plotting function fieldplot. Check the docstring for fieldplot for further information.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Optikos.fieldplot!"},{"category":"type","location":"#Optikos.FieldPlot","page":"Home","text":"FieldPlot is the plot type associated with plotting function fieldplot. Check the docstring for fieldplot for further information.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Optikos.FieldPlot"},{"category":"function","location":"#Optikos.phaseplot","page":"Home","text":"No docstring defined.\n\nPlot type\n\nThe plot type alias for the phaseplot function is PhasePlot.\n\nAttributes\n\ncolormap =  :hsv  — Colormap for phase display — should be cyclic\n\nunits =  :mm  — Defines the units of the plot\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Optikos.phaseplot"},{"category":"function","location":"#Optikos.phaseplot!","page":"Home","text":"phaseplot! is the mutating variant of plotting function phaseplot. Check the docstring for phaseplot for further information.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Optikos.phaseplot!"},{"category":"type","location":"#Optikos.PhasePlot","page":"Home","text":"PhasePlot is the plot type associated with plotting function phaseplot. Check the docstring for phaseplot for further information.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Optikos.PhasePlot"}]
